prompt:
Our kiosk provisioning agent reads its settings from small INI files kept on the device flash. I need a dependency-free scanner for them in C17: no malloc, no globals, single pass over the text, all memory supplied by the caller. Create `ini.h` and `ini.c` in this directory; the acceptance tests in `test_ini.c` build against them via `make test`.

The header must declare exactly this API:

```c
typedef struct {
    char *base;   /* caller-provided storage */
    size_t cap;   /* total bytes available */
    size_t used;  /* bytes handed out so far */
} ini_arena;

typedef struct {
    const char *section;  /* "" for pairs before the first [section] */
    const char *key;
    const char *value;
    size_t line;          /* 1-based line the pair appeared on */
} ini_pair;

enum {
    INI_OK       = 0,
    INI_EARG     = -1,   /* bad call arguments */
    INI_ESECTION = -2,   /* malformed [section] header */
    INI_EKEY     = -3,   /* missing '=' or empty key */
    INI_EQUOTE   = -4,   /* unterminated quote or unknown escape */
    INI_ETRAIL   = -5,   /* text after a closing quote */
    INI_ENOMEM   = -6    /* arena or pair table exhausted */
};

void ini_arena_init(ini_arena *a, void *storage, size_t cap);

long ini_parse(const char *text, ini_arena *a,
               ini_pair *pairs, size_t max_pairs,
               size_t *err_line, size_t *err_col);
```

`ini_parse` walks the whole text once, appends one `ini_pair` per key/value line, and returns the pair count (>= 0) on success or one of the negative codes above. Every section/key/value string is copied into the arena and NUL-terminated; the pairs must stay valid until the caller recycles the arena, so never point into `text`. On success, set `*err_line` and `*err_col` to 0; on a parse error set them to the 1-based line and column described below. Either pointer may be NULL, in which case just skip writing it. `INI_EARG` covers `text`, `a`, or `pairs` being NULL and `max_pairs == 0`.

Grammar, applied line by line (strip one trailing `\r` first; columns are 1-based byte positions in the stripped line):

- Blank lines and full-line comments are skipped. A comment line is one whose first non-blank character is `;` or `#`. Those characters are NOT comment starters elsewhere: an unquoted value keeps any `;` or `#` inside it.
- `[name]` switches the current section. The name is trimmed of surrounding blanks and must be non-empty. The header may have blanks around it but nothing else on the line.
- `key = value` lines split at the FIRST `=`. Key and value are trimmed of surrounding blanks; the key must be non-empty, the value may be empty. Later `=` characters belong to the value. Duplicate keys are legal and every occurrence is appended in document order; the same section may be reopened.
- If the trimmed value starts with `"`, it is a quoted value: everything up to the matching close quote is taken verbatim (leading/trailing blanks inside are kept), with exactly four escapes decoded: `\"`, `\\`, `\n`, `\t`. Any other character after a backslash is an error. After the closing quote only blanks may remain on the line.

Error positions (first error wins; stop scanning immediately):

- `INI_ESECTION`: header without `]` or with an empty name -> column of the `[`; non-blank text after the `]` -> column of that text.
- `INI_EKEY`: non-comment line without `=` -> column of its first non-blank character; empty key -> column of the `=`.
- `INI_EQUOTE`: unterminated quoted value -> column of the opening quote; unknown escape -> column of the backslash.
- `INI_ETRAIL`: non-blank text after the closing quote -> column of that text.
- `INI_ENOMEM`: arena too small for the next string, or `pairs` already holds `max_pairs` entries when another pair shows up -> line of the offending pair, column 0.

Arena discipline: `ini_arena_init` just records the storage block and resets `used`; `ini_parse` bump-allocates from it and never frees. Text with no pairs at all (empty string, only comments/blanks) is a successful parse returning 0. The last line participates even without a trailing newline. Build with `make test`; it compiles with -Wall -Wextra -Werror, so keep the code warning-clean.
